### Full Test Scenario - Create users and posts
### Step 1: Create first user
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "alice",
  "email": "alice@blog.com",
  "password": "alice123"
}

###

### Step 2: Create second user
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "bob",
  "email": "bob@blog.com",
  "password": "bob456"
}

###

### Step 3: Get all users (should see alice and bob)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/users
Accept: application/json

###

### Step 4: Create blog post by alice (authorId: 1 or check from step 3)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/posts
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Alice's Journey with Spring Boot",
  "content": "Today I learned about AOP and how powerful it is for cross-cutting concerns like logging.",
  "authorId": 1
}

###

### Step 5: Create blog post by bob (authorId: 2 or check from step 3)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/posts
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Bob's Guide to Database Migrations",
  "content": "Flyway makes database versioning simple and reliable. Here's what I learned...",
  "authorId": 2
}

###

### Step 6: Get all blog posts (should see posts from both alice and bob)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/posts
Accept: application/json

###

### Error Scenario 1: Try to create post with non-existent author
POST http://localhost:8080/api/posts
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Post by ghost author",
  "content": "This should fail validation",
  "authorId": 999
}

###

### Error Scenario 2: Try to create user with duplicate username
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "alice",
  "email": "alice_new@blog.com",
  "password": "differentpassword"
}

